<font color="#FF0000">ARTHUR'S PAGE</font><br>
<tt>Sun Jul 13 12:30:56 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Arthur Varanelli:<br><br>
Welcome home, Brother!  Your page is WELL Done.  Thanks for sharing not only good information but a good example for other Vets to follow.<br>
I drove balls of O.D Reynolds Wrap around the II, III and IV Corps area supporting fine men like you.  I didn't get to see everything you guys did (Kept My eyes closed alot!) but I did manage to stay cool under fire (I pissed my pants frequently!)<br>
I may be wrong (I usually am, but at least I'm consistant) when I assume that you were a cannon cocker in Viet Nam.<br>
I remember the 175's barking just outside the door of my humble abode.  Artillery robbed me of my first pieces of arrogance, innocence and ignorance.  <br>
Witness this fire mission through the eyes of an FNG... ME!<br><br>
                     &quot;The Show&quot;<br><br>
Dust and spiders fall from the rafters<br>
     each time the big guns roar.<br>
Rickety cots creak and dance <br>
     across the rough plank floor.<br>
I squint my eyes and plug my ears,<br>
     as I roll in a pool of sweat.<br>
But sleep is shattered by the cannons' report<br>
     and slinks from their resounding threat.<br>
Once outside, in the moonless dark<br>
     I struggle to gain my senses.<br>
Awake, at last, I take a seat,<br>
     near a sea of barbed wire fences.<br>
Fingers of orange from each muzzle flash,<br>
     peal back the darkest night.<br>
Briefly, the shadows of artillerymen<br>
     are etched in the blinding light.<br>
Burning powder stings the nostrils<br>
     and poisons every tepid breath.<br>
All night I watch these thundering giants<br>
     fill the shy with bursting death.<br>
Dawn's light came slowly creeping,<br>
     climbing higher through the Nipa Palm.<br>
The world grew quiet and the air turned clean<br>
     and all seemed still and calm.<br>
I rose from my seat, since the show was over,<br>
     and I rubbed my stiffened knees.<br>
Pensively, I sought the horizon,<br>
     seeing beyond the most distant trees.<br>
Visions of death gripped my mind,<br>
     filled with the dead and dying.<br>
I squinted my eyes and plugged my ears<br>
     but I could not squelch their crying.<br>
The booming guns were silent, <br>
     as I hung my head in shame.<br>
I recognized their deadly purpose,<br>
     and I quit my foolish game.<br>
Tonight, if the big guns fire,<br>
     I will stay in my soddened bed.<br>
I may not sleep, but maybe I won't smell...<br>
     nor see... nor hear the dead.<br><br>
from &quot;Scars and Stripes, Forever&quot; by Edward Ramon<br><br>
Hope you like it, Arthur.  Hang Tough!<br>
Mustang Two Four
